Additional details

With Emerson's award-winning and patented smartest technology, the flashing "12: 00" Display is a thing of the past. The ER100301 Digital tuning clock radio automatically sets itself on the first use to the correct year, month, date, day, and time. The clock radio features Bluetooth V4.1 digital tuning FM radio. Includes a USB output for mobile charging (2.1a 5V) and a large and easy-to-read LED display. The alarm can be programmed to operate on weekdays only, weekends only, or all seven days of the week. Set the alarm to wake you to your favorite FM music or news station, buzzer alarm or programmable sleep-to music timer. The clock radio adjusts itself automatically for daylight savings time and leap year, as well as maintains the correct time when the power returns after power outages. Getting out of bed will no longer be a chore with the help of the ER100301

From the manufacturer

With Emerson's award-winning and Patented smartset technology, the flashing "12: 00" Display is a thing of the past. The ER100301 Digital tuning clock radio automatically sets itself on the first use to the correct year, Month, date, day, and time. The clock radio features Bluetooth V4.1 digital tuning FM radio. Includes a USB output for mobile charging (2.1a 5V) and a large and easy-to-read LED display. The alarm can be programmed to operate on weekdays only, weekends only, or all seven days of the week. Set the alarm to wake you to your favorite FM music or news station, buzzer alarm or programmable sleep-to music timer. The clock radio adjusts itself automatically for daylight savings time and leap year, as well as maintains the correct time when the power returns after power outages. Getting out of bed will no longer be a chore with the help of the ER100301 Bluetooth V4.1 USB output for mobile charging 2.1a 5V digital tuning FM radio, 20 station memories easy-to-read, 1.4 Cyan LED clock display, dimmer control easy to program patented smartset automatic time setting system automatically sets itself to the correct year, Month, date, day and time as soon as you plug it in and after every power interruption button Cell battery (included) maintains time & Alarm settings

Customers say

Customers appreciate the clock radio's automatic time setting, adjustable brightness with three levels, and pleasant greenish-blue numerals. Moreover, the display is easy to read from across the room, and customers like its appearance. However, the ease of use and functionality receive mixed feedback - while some find it easy to set and use, others say the controls and setup are complicated, and while some report it works great, others mention it stopped working after a year. Additionally, the sound quality is mixed, with some finding it decent while others say it's not loud enough.

  • Francis R. Scallatino
    4.0 out of 5 starsVerified Purchase
    Fantastic alarm clock, not a great speaker.
    Reviewed in the United States on August 23, 2020
    Pattern Name: Speaker
    Product received: Jul 29, 2020 Original date of this review: Aug 22, 2020 I recently lost my last alarm clock after 10 years of faithful service, this is my first one since then. I honestly think I should've switched sooner because this is an awesome... See more
    Product received: Jul 29, 2020
    Original date of this review: Aug 22, 2020

    I recently lost my last alarm clock after 10 years of faithful service, this is my first one since then. I honestly think I should've switched sooner because this is an awesome product! You plug it in and it automatically sets the date and time (You may still need to adjust to the correct time out of the box but after that it should be fine). It has not just one but 2 alarms you can set (either for the entire week, just weekdays or just weekends, sat/sun). It has a nice, fat snooze button in the middle so you don't have to feel around too long to find it if you're just waking up. It seems to pick up really clear radio signals; I counted around 16 working channels with a wide variety of music and whatnot. The Bluetooth pairing works flawlessly so far, it's quite quick to connect and doesn't have any trouble staying connected. The range doesn't seem too great, though. The jack for the Aux cord works great as well if you don't want to connect via Bluetooth. Finally, the nightlight seems good. I hate having lights on at night but I did test to see how bright it was anyway. Gives a good amount of light in what would otherwise be a pitch-black room. It's not bright enough to navigate efficiently, but if you're just looking for a little bit of light to fill the room, this should be fine.

    Now some gripes I have with this product. First off, I kind of like the simplicity of the hardware, but considering how many functions it has, that also leads to some, in my opinion, minor downsides. For example, if you're listening to anything via Bluetooth/radio/aux, you can't change the display lightning, or check/change your alarms' settings. Also, I don't really listen to radio very often and I much rather use Bluetooth than aux to listen to music, but I can't really use the sleep mode if I want to do this. It does work in the sense that it turns off the Bluetooth, but the music continues playing on my phone after it shuts itself off automatically. It thankfully doesn't do this if I turn it off manually, but this is kind of a useless function, my case..

    Finally, the sound quality. It's standard radio sound quality. It has a tiny little section in the back for minimal fidelity sound, but that's it. I tested the range and it only reaches down to around 70Hz with a steep drop off in volume afterwards, though still barely audible down to around 30Hz, and reaches up to around 15,000Hz on the high end, completely cutting out at that point. It also buzzes a bit at certain low frequencies. I've managed to force some decent sound out of it with an equalizer, but in the long run it just makes it quieter. The speaker does get decently loud if you're in doors, but it doesn't travel very far if you're listening to music outside.

    Conclusion: If you're looking for an alarm clock with a speaker, this is an amazing product. If you're looking for a speaker with alarm clock functionalities, look elsewhere.

    5.0 out of 5 starsVerified Purchase
    This is one really great clock radio!
    Reviewed in the United States on September 1, 2017
    Pattern Name: Speaker
    Alarm clocks come in all sizes and shapes with all kinds of different features. I actually didn't want an alarm clock for myself, but rather my wife wanted a radio to use in the kitchen. I got her this one because it looked like it might be easier to use than her last... See more
    Alarm clocks come in all sizes and shapes with all kinds of different features. I actually didn't want an alarm clock for myself, but rather my wife wanted a radio to use in the kitchen. I got her this one because it looked like it might be easier to use than her last one and also because she has poor vision and the picture showed nice large numbers. But when it came she told me she only wanted a radio, not an alarm clock. So, rather than send it back, I decided to swap it for my old alarm clock which was adequate but wasn't anything to rave about.

    This clock though, is something to rave about. This is the first clock I have ever owned that accurately and easily sets the local time all by itself! You just set the correct time zone and a few seconds later the right time is displayed. Nice. It also has two different alarms. That lets you set alarms for your work week and also for the weekend. I get up at 5 am during the week. On the weekends I sleep in till 8. I have both alarms set and I'm able to pick only M-F for one alarm and only Sat-Sun for the other alarm. As an old TV ad used to say, "Just set it and forget it!" Controlling the alarm when it goes off is easy too. If you do nothing it will turn off by itself after 10 minutes I believe. If you want it to snooze, just tap the front of the silver colored plate on the top and it will start the alarm again in a few minutes and if you want to turn off the alarm completely, just tap a button on the left side of the top and it goes silent until the next time that alarm should sound. Other nice features include an easy to turn on and off radio function that also has room for several preset stations. The clock numbers are cyan in color, which is easy to see. Plus there are 3 different levels of brightness for the numbers (really bright, medium, and dim) which you can change just by tapping a switch on the top of the clock. Speaking of the top of the clock, if you tap the back of the top plate it turns on/off a bright night light that is on the bottom of the clock. And you can also charge a phone or bluetooth device with a handy usb power connection on the back. And there is also an AUX plug on it, although I can't recall if it is AUX out or in. Haven't felt the need to use that function yet. And finally, like most good alarm clocks, this one has a place you can install a battery, so that you won't be late to work should there be a power outage where you live.

    3.0 out of 5 starsVerified Purchase
    Emerson ER100301: SO close but not quite. This is the newest version w/ three brightness levels and a high amp USB charger.
    Reviewed in the United States on September 2, 2017
    Pattern Name: Speaker
    1.
    There have been many average reviews of previous designs for both the Emerson CKS1507/CKS1708 and iTOMA CKS507, and this will be an average review of the new one. Aw, what! They didn't fix everything mentioned by 1000+ Amazon reviews? NOPE. I wanted to love... See more
    There have been many average reviews of previous designs for both the Emerson CKS1507/CKS1708 and iTOMA CKS507, and this will be an average review of the new one. Aw, what! They didn't fix everything mentioned by 1000+ Amazon reviews? NOPE.

    I wanted to love this as an alarm clock, I wanted it to be a perfect way to wake gently, I wanted easy to read time and day fields (including the date would have been nice too). But no, these few basic features were poorly designed and executed in this clock. The truly sad thing is that this is still the best you can get if you want large text, day of the week, and dual alarms. Other clocks have issues such as being unreadable at low angles, no USB charging, battery power only, really ugly:), etc.

    Features I do love:
    *The lowest brightness level is perfect...on weekdays (explained below and in photos).
    *The exterior design and cyan color are very nice looking.
    *The night light is quite useful and set at a really good brightness level.
    *The time display is large enough to be read from 30 feet away.
    *It's a plug-in, not a cheap travel clock.
    *Day of the week. However I feel the day is too small since it may only be read from about six feet away.

    Things I hate and which Emerson Co. should have fixed:
    *The volume is still forced to a stupidly loud scale...i.e. Even level 1 out of 10 can easily wake you from across the room. Emerson's idea of 'waking up gently' is starting at a too-loud level 1 then rapidly increasing the volume to 8. Believe me, you will be cussing when it reaches level 4 after only 20 seconds. Their instructions stating the alarm volume will not exceed the radio volume you set, is still false. Come on, a simple analog volume knob, 50 cents, problem solved!
    *Then you can see in my photos that they did fix the brightness by adding a low level setting. Brightness is just perfect on weekdays, but what the heck happens when 11:59 PM Friday turns into 12 AM Saturday? The perfect weekday brightnes is cut in half as soon as the red Saturday LED turns on. You cannot read the time on Saturday and Sunday with the brightness on its lowest setting.

    Moot 'features':
    *Bluetooth, because it is mono speaker, so just for fun I guess?
    *Passive sub-woofer radiator on the bottom, again because it is mono.
    *The 'BEEP' alarm is far less obnoxious than the radio, but still at the forced volume.
    *Surprise! The weekday/weekend alarms are sort of useless, and here's why. I almost always wake before the alarm, so I turn it OFF in the morning then back ON every night anyway. That means it's off Friday morning and back on Sunday night...with no need for the 'weekday' alarm feature.

    To conclude, I am keeping the Emerson ER100301 as a great clock, but with imperfect alarm-clock features.
